I think you're encountering the overhead of having to recreate the TensorRT engine to accommodate the dynamic input shape.
You can use warmup runs which cover the full range of the expected input shapes and enable engine caching to avoid this overhead at inference time. 
e.g.
```
ort_sess= onnxruntime.InferenceSession(modelfile, providers=[('TensorrtExecutionProvider', {"trt_engine_cache_enable", "true"})], )
# confirm setting 
ort_sess.get_provider_options()
```

In [3]: ort_sess= onnxruntime.InferenceSession(modelfile, providers=[('TensorrtExecutionProvider', {"trt_engine_cache_enable", "true"})],
   ...: )

Falling back to ['CUDAExecutionProvider', 'CPUExecutionProvider'] and retrying.

issue.body:
when the model support dynamic batch ，the input shape [ -1,-1,80],  how can  warm up?  because of the dynamic batch , I do know the warmup batchsize number ,can it use min_batchsize and max _batchsize to warmup?

_Originally posted by @liroda in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/12120#issuecomment-1218914542_

body: If inputs have dynamic shapes, there should be two warmup runs that cover upper bound and lower bound of the input shapes. For instance, a model has input with dynamic shape [A, B]. Dimension A's shape range is expected to be [a1, a2] in inference and dimension B's shape range is [b1, b2]. The first warmup runs should run on a input with shape [a1, b1] and the second warmup runs on a input with shape [a2, b2]. This makes sure engine built in the warmup session can cover the whole shape ranges in inference, otherwise engine will be rebuilt in inference, which could take long time and slow down inference.
ok ,I will try. thank you very much, very clearly.
